Here’s a clear breakdown of the AWS VPN Connection — this ties together the Customer Gateway (your router/firewall) and the Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) or Transit Gateway (TGW) on the AWS side:

🔑 What is a VPN Connection?
A VPN Connection in AWS is the secure link between your on-premises network and your AWS VPC.

It’s established using two redundant IPsec tunnels for high availability.

It requires both:

Customer Gateway (CGW) → Represents your physical router/firewall.

Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) or Transit Gateway (TGW) → AWS-managed endpoint.

⚙️ Step-by-Step Flow
Define Customer Gateway → Public IP of your router/firewall.

Create VGW or TGW → Attach to your VPC.

Establish VPN Connection → AWS generates configuration files for your router.

Configure IPsec Tunnels → Two tunnels for redundancy.

Update Route Tables → Direct traffic destined for on-premises through the VPN.

Secure Communication → Encrypted traffic flows between your data center and AWS VPC.

📊 Key Benefits
Security → IPsec encryption ensures confidentiality.

Redundancy → Two tunnels for failover.

Flexibility → Works with VGW (single VPC) or TGW (multi-VPC).

Hybrid Cloud → Extends your private network into AWS seamlessly.

✅ Bottom Line: The VPN Connection is the glue that binds your on-premises infrastructure to AWS, enabling hybrid cloud setups with secure, encrypted communication.